WEBVTT

00:06.131 --> 00:09.843
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

00:09.843 --> 00:10.886
[hammer clanks]

00:10.886 --> 00:15.891
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:15.891 --> 00:17.434
<i>‐ My name is Dan Burlows.</i>

00:17.434 --> 00:18.810
<i>I'm from Taylorsville,</i>
<i>Kentucky.</i>

00:18.810 --> 00:21.063
<i>I am a metallurgical engineer.</i>

00:21.063 --> 00:23.106
I really look at metallurgy
and material science

00:23.106 --> 00:25.442
and being an engineer
as kind of the other side

00:25.442 --> 00:28.237
<i>of the same coin</i>
<i>as bladesmithing.</i>

00:28.237 --> 00:30.822
<i>Bladesmithing is very</i>
<i>important to me because it is</i>

00:30.822 --> 00:34.493
this perfect blend of art
and science and skill.

00:34.493 --> 00:35.827
<i>‐ My name is John Sims.</i>

00:35.827 --> 00:37.788
I'm a 21‐year‐old
hobbyist bladesmith.

00:37.788 --> 00:40.958
When I'm forging, I'm just
in my own little world.

00:40.958 --> 00:43.794
<i>Being a quiet</i>
<i>and softer‐spoken individual,</i>

00:43.794 --> 00:45.837
people tend to
think that I'm an ass[bleep].

00:45.837 --> 00:46.880
<i>I'm really not.</i>

00:46.880 --> 00:48.006
<i>Just come approach me;</i>

00:48.006 --> 00:49.216
<i>I'll talk to you for hours.</i>

00:49.216 --> 00:50.884
<i>‐ My name is Andrew Smith.</i>

00:50.884 --> 00:54.054
I made my first blade,
and after that, freaked out.

00:54.054 --> 00:55.931
Just completely
geeked out over knives,

00:55.931 --> 00:57.975
<i>and I've been making</i>
<i>knives ever since.</i>

00:57.975 --> 00:59.559
<i>If I win $10,000,</i>

00:59.559 --> 01:01.144
first thing I'm doing
is getting some wings.

01:01.144 --> 01:02.521
Second thing I'm doing‐‐

01:02.521 --> 01:04.147
I don't know,
maybe buy a kayak.

01:04.147 --> 01:06.066
Something like that.
[laughs]

01:06.066 --> 01:07.192
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:07.192 --> 01:08.777
<i>‐ My name's Josh Nikolaidis.</i>

01:08.777 --> 01:10.779
The reason why I started
bladesmithing is because

01:10.779 --> 01:12.531
I was practicing a lot
of survival skills,

01:12.531 --> 01:14.366
and all the store‐bought
knives that I had

01:14.366 --> 01:15.701
just turned
out to be junk,

01:15.701 --> 01:16.994
so I figured I could
make my own.

01:16.994 --> 01:18.620
<i>My friends would describe me</i>

01:18.620 --> 01:20.747
<i>as the goofy redneck</i>
<i>from down the road.</i>

01:20.747 --> 01:22.374
<i>I would describe me as...</i>

01:22.374 --> 01:23.959
the goofy redneck
down the road.

01:23.959 --> 01:25.377
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:25.377 --> 01:27.129
‐ Bladesmiths,
welcome to The Forge.

01:27.129 --> 01:28.672
You are about to experience
a competition

01:28.672 --> 01:31.008
in three rounds
that's designed to test

01:31.008 --> 01:33.594
every aspect of your
bladesmithing capabilities

01:33.594 --> 01:35.220
in front of a panel
of expert judges

01:35.220 --> 01:36.847
who will tell us which of you

01:36.847 --> 01:38.515
is the next
"Forged in Fire" champion,

01:38.515 --> 01:41.602
leaving here with a check
for $10,000.

01:41.602 --> 01:43.395
Let's meet your judges now.

01:43.395 --> 01:45.397
Up first, two‐time
"Forged in Fire" champion

01:45.397 --> 01:46.982
Ben Abbott.

01:46.982 --> 01:48.567
Next, historic weapons
recreation specialist

01:48.567 --> 01:50.277
David Baker.

01:50.277 --> 01:53.989
And last, edged weapons
specialist, Doug Marcaida.

01:53.989 --> 01:57.367
Today we're gonna pay homage
to our presidents.

01:57.367 --> 02:00.037
We're gonna honor
one of my favorite presidents,

02:00.037 --> 02:02.289
President Theodore Roosevelt.

02:02.289 --> 02:05.500
He became the 26th president
of the United States.

02:05.500 --> 02:08.378
He was born sickly and weak,
but he overcame adversity

02:08.378 --> 02:10.130
to win the Nobel Peace Prize,

02:10.130 --> 02:14.259
and he led the first
United States volunteer Cavalry

02:14.259 --> 02:16.678
<i>during</i>
<i>the Spanish‐American War,</i>

02:16.678 --> 02:19.348
and his unit was known
as the Rough Riders.

02:19.348 --> 02:21.058
Today there will be no
signature blades

02:21.058 --> 02:22.851
in your signature style.

02:22.851 --> 02:25.103
Instead, we'll
be giving you a piece

02:25.103 --> 02:28.482
of W1 round stock
from which to forge this.

02:28.482 --> 02:33.111
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:33.111 --> 02:35.364
A Rough Riders bowie,

02:35.364 --> 02:38.492
issued to everyone
in the Rough Riders unit.

02:38.492 --> 02:41.870
Today you'll be making
exacting copies of that blade.

02:41.870 --> 02:44.665
<i>Your blades must fall within</i>
<i>the following parameters.</i>

02:44.665 --> 02:47.042
<i>The length of your blade,</i>
<i>as measured from tip to guard,</i>

02:47.042 --> 02:49.378
<i>must be between</i>
<i>9 and 9 1/2 inches.</i>

02:49.378 --> 02:51.755
<i>The width of your blade</i>
<i>as measured at the base</i>

02:51.755 --> 02:55.258
<i>must be at least 2 inches,</i>
<i>and you must include a clip</i>

02:55.258 --> 02:57.594
<i>that is between</i>
<i>3 and 3 1/2 inches.</i>

02:57.594 --> 03:00.180
We've actually included
the design parameters

03:00.180 --> 03:03.850
and your steel in the scrolls
on top of your anvils.

03:03.850 --> 03:06.019
Go ahead and open those up.

03:06.019 --> 03:07.479
<i>‐ I'm nervous.</i>

03:07.479 --> 03:08.689
<i>When I'm making</i>
<i>something on my own,</i>

03:08.689 --> 03:10.023
if I mess it up,

03:10.023 --> 03:11.733
I can adjust the design
as I go,

03:11.733 --> 03:13.235
<i>but with this one,</i>
<i>you've gotta</i>

03:13.235 --> 03:15.445
<i>make it exactly that way.</i>

03:15.445 --> 03:17.364
If not, it's not
a Rough Rider bowie.

03:17.364 --> 03:18.949
‐ Keep in mind that,
in the second round,

03:18.949 --> 03:20.450
you'll attach handles
to these bowies,

03:20.450 --> 03:21.868
turning them
into fully‐functional

03:21.868 --> 03:23.578
Rough Rider blades

03:23.578 --> 03:25.956
that will be tested
for strength and durability

03:25.956 --> 03:27.749
in a moose‐antler chop,

03:27.749 --> 03:30.794
and for edge retention,
in a fish slice.

03:30.794 --> 03:32.838
I remind you that,
after the time runs out,

03:32.838 --> 03:35.215
one of you will be selected
to leave The Forge.

03:35.215 --> 03:36.758
Good luck, Bladesmiths.

03:36.758 --> 03:39.469
Your three hours starts now.

03:39.469 --> 03:42.639
<i>[rock music]</i>

03:42.639 --> 03:44.266
‐ When forging, sometimes

03:44.266 --> 03:46.309
you let the blade tell you
what it wants to be.

03:46.309 --> 03:47.436
Not today.

03:47.436 --> 03:49.187
‐ It's brutal; I mean,

03:49.187 --> 03:51.273
when a prop company
or a movie company comes to me,

03:51.273 --> 03:54.901
you get a picture sent to you
with dimensions.

03:54.901 --> 03:56.570
You don't get to change
the parameters.

03:56.570 --> 03:58.071
You don't get to put
your spin on it.

03:58.071 --> 03:59.614
‐ Now, Dave,
you ride horses a lot.

03:59.614 --> 04:00.824
With these blades,
how do you think

04:00.824 --> 04:02.325
they carried them on their hip?

04:02.325 --> 04:04.202
‐ They were usually carried
on the left side.

04:04.202 --> 04:05.745
Your pistol was on your right.

04:05.745 --> 04:07.873
‐ I would also posit
that it was

04:07.873 --> 04:09.291
a good choice
for the Rough Riders,

04:09.291 --> 04:11.251
'cause it's a very
American knife.

04:11.251 --> 04:13.044
♪ ♪

04:13.044 --> 04:14.504
‐ First thing I do
is pull out the calipers

04:14.504 --> 04:16.214
and start measuring.

04:16.214 --> 04:18.633
I figure that the sooner
I can get a drawing

04:18.633 --> 04:22.220
with dimensions,
get my engineer on, the better.

04:22.220 --> 04:25.640
‐ With this 1‐inch round
of W1 and 12 inches, Ben,

04:25.640 --> 04:27.476
there's plenty of steel there

04:27.476 --> 04:30.103
to get the width
that these guys need.

04:30.103 --> 04:32.481
They just need a lot of skill
to make it happen.

04:32.481 --> 04:34.775
‐ Right, because
if you just hit it flat,

04:34.775 --> 04:36.985
it goes equally in length
as it does width.

04:36.985 --> 04:38.945
[hammering]

04:38.945 --> 04:40.697
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:40.697 --> 04:42.365
<i>‐ When I first saw</i>
<i>the challenge, I was like,</i>

04:42.365 --> 04:44.075
"Cool, we're making a bowie,"
but then whenever

04:44.075 --> 04:46.536
<i>I figured out it</i>
<i>has to be the actual replica,</i>

04:46.536 --> 04:47.996
that's when the nerves
set in a little.

04:47.996 --> 04:49.664
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:49.664 --> 04:52.959
‐ So Josh is drawing
his steel out lengthwise.

04:52.959 --> 04:55.545
‐ Right, he's got
a barbed steel

04:55.545 --> 04:57.839
that's maybe
an inch and a quarter wide,

04:57.839 --> 05:01.259
already longer than the knife
that's on display.

05:01.259 --> 05:03.553
‐ So you really want
to fuller it to width.

05:03.553 --> 05:05.722
‐ What are the best ways
to fuller here?

05:05.722 --> 05:07.265
‐ Blue has fullering dies,
and you have to go at it

05:07.265 --> 05:09.601
from right angles,
how you usually do it.

05:09.601 --> 05:11.478
‐ Which isn't happening.

05:11.478 --> 05:14.523
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:14.523 --> 05:16.983
‐ I'm just measuring
every time I turn around,

05:16.983 --> 05:19.319
and then I'm like, "Well,
I have all this excess steel

05:19.319 --> 05:22.072
in the back that I don't need
to be carrying back and forth.

05:22.072 --> 05:23.281
[buzzing]

05:23.281 --> 05:24.699
‐ Guys, I'm watching Josh work,

05:24.699 --> 05:26.326
and looking at it right now,

05:26.326 --> 05:27.911
it's definitely
not wide enough.

05:27.911 --> 05:29.037
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:29.037 --> 05:32.332
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

05:32.332 --> 05:35.752
‐ Andrew is fullering sideways
to get the width that he needs.

05:35.752 --> 05:37.838
‐ Andrew has already
figured out problem one...

05:37.838 --> 05:39.381
‐ Yeah.
‐ Which is great.

05:39.381 --> 05:40.924
<i>‐ Now I got the spine</i>
<i>of the blade</i>

05:40.924 --> 05:42.509
<i>pretty close</i>
<i>to the thickness I want,</i>

05:42.509 --> 05:44.344
so I move over to the anvil,

05:44.344 --> 05:46.096
do a lot of the rest
of the work by hand.

05:46.096 --> 05:48.807
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:48.807 --> 05:50.183
‐ He's already got
2 inches in there, man.

05:50.183 --> 05:52.310
He's doing a really great job.

05:52.310 --> 05:56.857
‐ Dan and Andrew, the two
smiths that started on blue

05:56.857 --> 05:58.900
perpendicular
to its normal axis

05:58.900 --> 06:01.486
are the only two smiths
that have 2‐inch‐wide blades.

06:01.486 --> 06:04.823
‐ We should see some
beautiful Rough Rider bowies.

06:04.823 --> 06:07.158
They shouldn't be Rough Riders;
they should be "smooth riders."

06:07.158 --> 06:09.744
‐ Oh, yeah. Easy riders.
‐ Easy riders.

06:09.744 --> 06:12.289
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:12.289 --> 06:14.916
‐ I have to reach this
2‐inch width requirement,

06:14.916 --> 06:16.960
<i>so I'm working off</i>
<i>the side of the dies,</i>

06:16.960 --> 06:19.254
just widening
everything really nice.

06:19.254 --> 06:21.506
‐ Look what our man
John's just discovered.

06:21.506 --> 06:22.883
‐ Oh, yeah.

06:22.883 --> 06:25.385
‐ The little
"Smithy see, smithy do."

06:25.385 --> 06:28.513
‐ I'm gonna continue to spread
this material out a little more

06:28.513 --> 06:31.224
until I hit just over
the 2‐inch mark,

06:31.224 --> 06:33.643
so I have meat to play with
when I go to the grinder.

06:33.643 --> 06:36.605
‐ Bladesmiths,
one hour has elapsed!

06:36.605 --> 06:39.065
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:39.065 --> 06:41.234
‐ The power hammer is
a fantastic piece of equipment,

06:41.234 --> 06:43.820
but it is really, really easy
to get carried away,

06:43.820 --> 06:45.906
<i>and while hammering,</i>

06:45.906 --> 06:49.451
I see something at the very
last 2 inches of my blade.

06:49.451 --> 06:51.328
It's a cold shut.

06:51.328 --> 06:53.330
The best thing to do is to just
get the angle grinder out

06:53.330 --> 06:56.791
<i>and grind off that excess.</i>

06:56.791 --> 06:58.460
<i>I grind away the cold shut.</i>

06:58.460 --> 07:00.253
<i>It's a little deeper</i>
<i>than I'm expecting,</i>

07:00.253 --> 07:02.339
<i>but I still have a good amount</i>
<i>of material there.</i>

07:02.339 --> 07:04.215
<i>I feel a little scared,</i>

07:04.215 --> 07:06.551
but I think that
has to do with the judges.

07:06.551 --> 07:08.511
Dave looks really friendly...

07:08.511 --> 07:09.804
‐ [chuckling]

07:09.804 --> 07:11.264
‐ Until he's looking at you,

07:11.264 --> 07:13.475
and then you have
that cold, steely stare...

07:13.475 --> 07:14.976
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:14.976 --> 07:17.979
That pierces the very fabric
of your soul.

07:17.979 --> 07:21.066
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:21.066 --> 07:22.651
<i>‐ My bowie looks very good.</i>

07:22.651 --> 07:25.362
<i>And then I go</i>
<i>slightly oversized,</i>

07:25.362 --> 07:27.197
<i>and that gives me</i>
<i>the chance to grind it</i>

07:27.197 --> 07:28.823
exactly where it needs to be.

07:28.823 --> 07:31.534
‐ The heat's
transformed Andrew's shirt

07:31.534 --> 07:32.827
to some cool design.

07:32.827 --> 07:34.204
What do you think
the F stands for?

07:34.204 --> 07:35.497
‐ Forging.

07:35.497 --> 07:37.832
‐ "Forged in Fire."
‐ Oh, yeah.

07:37.832 --> 07:41.211
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:41.211 --> 07:44.214
<i>‐ Working my steel, I'm</i>
<i>feeling good about the length,</i>

07:44.214 --> 07:46.174
<i>and then it dawns on me that</i>

07:46.174 --> 07:48.593
I have to make this
2 inches wide as well.

07:48.593 --> 07:50.804
Think I might have screwed up.

07:50.804 --> 07:52.222
I go over, and I start
trying to draw it out.

07:52.222 --> 07:53.473
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:53.473 --> 07:55.350
‐ Josh, now he's using
that same

07:55.350 --> 07:57.185
thick blue
width technique,

07:57.185 --> 08:00.188
but it's definitely gonna
have to come along fast.

08:00.188 --> 08:02.065
<i>‐ I am just chasing this,</i>

08:02.065 --> 08:03.775
<i>trying to get</i>
<i>that 2‐inch mark,</i>

08:03.775 --> 08:05.360
<i>but my blade is just getting</i>

08:05.360 --> 08:07.529
thinner and thinner
and thinner.

08:07.529 --> 08:09.114
‐ Josh is shaking his head.

08:09.114 --> 08:11.241
‐ Yeah, not a good sign.

08:11.241 --> 08:14.077
‐ I have no idea how
I'm gonna try to fix this.

08:14.077 --> 08:15.912
<i>I'm in panic mode,</i>

08:15.912 --> 08:18.707
and there's just not enough
time to forge a new blade.

08:18.707 --> 08:19.874
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

08:23.336 --> 08:26.005
‐ I am just chasing this,
trying to get that 2‐inch mark.
[hammer clanks]

08:26.005 --> 08:28.007
My blade's paper thin,
and we're gonna go

08:28.007 --> 08:29.884
chop into moose antlers.
Yay!

08:29.884 --> 08:32.846
I look at the clock,
and I decide

08:32.846 --> 08:34.347
<i>to stick with</i>
<i>what I have here.</i>

08:34.347 --> 08:37.183
<i>I hope that I've got it</i>
<i>in parameters.</i>

08:37.183 --> 08:40.812
<i>[rock music]</i>

08:40.812 --> 08:43.189
‐ I noticed that my bar
is looking a little long,

08:43.189 --> 08:47.152
so I take to the chop saw,
and I chop off the tip.

08:47.152 --> 08:48.570
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:48.570 --> 08:50.864
‐ John's blade
looks alarmingly short.

08:50.864 --> 08:51.865
‐ [bleep].

08:51.865 --> 08:53.158
<i>I cut too much off.</i>

08:53.158 --> 08:54.868
It's not looking good.

08:54.868 --> 08:56.870
<i>I just have to hope</i>
<i>that I can stretch it</i>

08:56.870 --> 08:58.788
<i>enough to make</i>
<i>the length requirements.</i>

08:58.788 --> 09:01.875
I realize that sometimes I make
way too much work for myself,

09:01.875 --> 09:03.376
<i>and I believe</i>
<i>I've just done that</i>

09:03.376 --> 09:05.712
<i>by cutting off</i>
<i>too much material.</i>

09:05.712 --> 09:07.047
‐ Thirty minutes,
bladesmiths!

09:07.047 --> 09:10.216
<i>[rock music]</i>

09:10.216 --> 09:12.177
‐ Dan seems
to be well on his way.

09:12.177 --> 09:13.887
I mean, he's got his
design and the profile

09:13.887 --> 09:15.221
of the blade
looking good.

09:15.221 --> 09:16.765
‐ I think Dan's
got it dialed in.

09:16.765 --> 09:19.100
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:19.100 --> 09:21.061
‐ I am at parameters,
but I'm holding it

09:21.061 --> 09:22.687
pretty damn close
on some of them.

09:22.687 --> 09:24.898
<i>I had to stretch out</i>
<i>a little bit more</i>

09:24.898 --> 09:26.232
<i>material than</i>
<i>I was comfortable with,</i>

09:26.232 --> 09:28.234
so now I'm looking
at a heat treat

09:28.234 --> 09:30.653
on an edge that's a little
thinner than I had wanted.

09:30.653 --> 09:32.572
<i>So I think to myself,</i>

09:32.572 --> 09:33.865
"I need to edge quench,
and that's it."

09:33.865 --> 09:36.034
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:36.034 --> 09:37.535
‐ Dan's gonna go
for an edge quench,

09:37.535 --> 09:38.536
which is very clever.

09:38.536 --> 09:43.958
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:43.958 --> 09:45.752
<i>‐ Right now,</i>
<i>I need to get my blade hard,</i>

09:45.752 --> 09:48.671
and I have never
successfully quenched W1.

09:48.671 --> 09:50.673
Every time I've tried
to quench W1, I've cracked it,

09:50.673 --> 09:52.133
which has only been twice.

09:52.133 --> 09:53.760
This is the third time.

09:53.760 --> 09:56.262
Third time's the charm.

09:56.262 --> 09:57.263
I just got an idea.

09:57.263 --> 09:58.431
<i>Then I remember, "Wait,</i>

09:58.431 --> 09:59.808
<i>"I have a piece of scrap W1</i>

09:59.808 --> 10:01.601
<i>from the billet</i>
<i>that I cut off."</i>

10:01.601 --> 10:03.770
Throw that in The Forge
to do a test heat treat.

10:03.770 --> 10:06.106
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:06.106 --> 10:07.565
Pull it out, prep the oil,

10:07.565 --> 10:09.150
<i>hit it with a file‐‐</i>
<i>no cracks.</i>

10:09.150 --> 10:10.735
I'm like, "All right."
[exhales]

10:10.735 --> 10:12.529
‐ Andrew did something
really interesting.

10:12.529 --> 10:15.156
He took a sacrificial
piece of metal, heated it up,

10:15.156 --> 10:17.283
quenched it,
and file touched it.

10:17.283 --> 10:19.077
That's smart work.

10:19.077 --> 10:22.080
‐ Now I just have to do
the same thing with my blade,

10:22.080 --> 10:23.873
and the whole time,
I'm just like,

10:23.873 --> 10:25.625
"Oh, man, this is‐‐
this is gonna be bad.

10:25.625 --> 10:27.085
This is gonna be bad."

10:27.085 --> 10:29.587
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:29.587 --> 10:31.798
Pull it out of the oil,
first thing,

10:31.798 --> 10:33.800
hit it with a file.

10:33.800 --> 10:34.968
[scraping]

10:34.968 --> 10:36.469
We're good; I got this round.

10:36.469 --> 10:39.514
<i>[rock music]</i>

10:39.514 --> 10:40.807
<i>‐ I'm at the grinder.</i>

10:40.807 --> 10:42.308
I've hogged off
all the material

10:42.308 --> 10:44.853
I think I need to hog off
before I quench my blade.

10:44.853 --> 10:47.313
Being that I don't have
a lot of experience with W1,

10:47.313 --> 10:50.692
<i>I'm not sure what it's going</i>
<i>to react to the quench like.</i>

10:50.692 --> 10:54.154
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:54.154 --> 10:56.281
<i>Feeling kind of apprehensive,</i>
<i>kind of nervous.</i>

10:56.281 --> 10:58.116
I do not want this to go wrong.

10:58.116 --> 10:59.159
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:59.159 --> 11:00.702
<i>After the quench,</i>

11:00.702 --> 11:01.661
<i>I check the blade</i>
<i>for straightness.</i>

11:01.661 --> 11:02.829
It's fairly straight.

11:02.829 --> 11:05.165
I don't see any major warps.

11:05.165 --> 11:09.210
<i>But it's not really looking</i>
<i>like the blade they wanted,</i>

11:09.210 --> 11:11.045
and that kind of
makes me worried.

11:11.045 --> 11:13.673
And I'm looking at Dan.

11:13.673 --> 11:16.134
He's doing really well.
His blade looks awesome.

11:17.177 --> 11:18.845
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:18.845 --> 11:20.847
‐ Josh, he's been
struggling a little bit

11:20.847 --> 11:21.973
trying to make the width.

11:21.973 --> 11:23.683
He now has a very thin blade.

11:23.683 --> 11:25.810
He's at the grinder.

11:25.810 --> 11:27.520
‐ I'm in a mad dash
to get this done.

11:27.520 --> 11:29.480
<i>Time's flying by.</i>

11:29.480 --> 11:31.524
So now I'm getting ready
to quench this W1 steel.

11:31.524 --> 11:32.901
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:32.901 --> 11:34.360
‐ Josh is in the quench
right now.

11:34.360 --> 11:36.029
<i>‐ I'm looking at it,</i>

11:36.029 --> 11:38.364
and I can tell
there is a warp to it.

11:38.364 --> 11:40.033
<i>I have forged it out too thin</i>

11:40.033 --> 11:41.993
<i>trying to meet that</i>
<i>2‐inch‐wide parameter,</i>

11:41.993 --> 11:44.829
and I've picked up a warp.

11:44.829 --> 11:50.001
‐ Five. Four. Three. Two. One.

11:50.001 --> 11:51.544
Bladesmiths,
shut down your machines.

11:51.544 --> 11:52.879
Drop your tools.

11:52.879 --> 11:55.882
This first round
of competition is over.

11:55.882 --> 11:58.092
<i>‐ Then I look over at all</i>
<i>the other competitors' blades.</i>

11:58.092 --> 12:00.887
<i>I'm not 100% if I made</i>
<i>parameters or not,</i>

12:00.887 --> 12:04.349
and I am just worried that I'm
gonna be the one going home.

12:04.349 --> 12:06.017
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:06.017 --> 12:07.060
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

12:07.060 --> 12:08.895
‐ Bladesmiths, today,

12:08.895 --> 12:11.356
we pay homage
to our 26th president

12:11.356 --> 12:13.399
of the United States,
Theodore Roosevelt,

12:13.399 --> 12:16.236
by asking you to forge
Rough Rider bowies

12:16.236 --> 12:18.696
to very exacting measurements.

12:18.696 --> 12:20.240
Now that those blades
have been tempered,

12:20.240 --> 12:21.741
here's a big problem.

12:21.741 --> 12:26.371
Three of your blades
did not make parameters.

12:26.371 --> 12:27.413
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:27.413 --> 12:28.831
‐ I'd like the three smiths

12:28.831 --> 12:30.375
who think
they missed parameters

12:30.375 --> 12:33.878
to take one step forward
right...now.

12:34.921 --> 12:37.924
<i>[tense music]</i>

12:37.924 --> 12:44.931
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:44.931 --> 12:47.809
Dan, take a step back,
my friend.

12:47.809 --> 12:49.185
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:49.185 --> 12:52.397
Andrew, go ahead
and step forward.

12:52.397 --> 12:53.606
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:53.606 --> 12:55.108
Gentlemen,

12:55.108 --> 12:56.776
your three blades
didn't make parameters

12:56.776 --> 12:58.111
in one way or another.

12:58.111 --> 12:59.946
I'm gonna let
David Baker explain.

12:59.946 --> 13:03.825
‐ John, your blade length
is under the minimum 9 inches.

13:03.825 --> 13:05.702
Andrew, your blade length

13:05.702 --> 13:07.912
is over the maximum
9 and a 1/2 inches.

13:07.912 --> 13:08.955
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:08.955 --> 13:10.456
Josh, your blade length

13:10.456 --> 13:12.792
is over the 9 and 1/2 inch
maximum length

13:12.792 --> 13:15.128
and under the 2‐inch
minimum width.

13:15.128 --> 13:16.629
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:16.629 --> 13:17.797
‐ Dan, you can relax.

13:17.797 --> 13:18.798
You're moving on
to the next

13:18.798 --> 13:20.508
round of competition.

13:20.508 --> 13:22.218
You three bladesmiths,
however‐‐

13:22.218 --> 13:24.971
we're gonna settle this
with a sudden death match.

13:24.971 --> 13:26.347
<i>[slicing]</i>

13:26.347 --> 13:28.016
Your knives will
be tested on merit,

13:28.016 --> 13:30.310
and you must earn
a spot in the next round.

13:30.310 --> 13:32.145
Best blades move forward.

13:32.145 --> 13:35.481
<i>‐ I have no idea</i>
<i>what is going to happen,</i>

13:35.481 --> 13:37.108
but I'm kind of nervous.

13:37.108 --> 13:41.654
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:41.654 --> 13:44.490
‐ John, Andrew, Josh,

13:44.490 --> 13:46.159
I'm going to take
each of your knives

13:46.159 --> 13:49.162
and baton them three times
into this nut here.

13:49.162 --> 13:52.331
Two of you will go forward,
and one of you will go home.

13:52.331 --> 13:53.332
John, you're up first.

13:53.332 --> 13:55.501
You ready?
‐ Yes.

13:55.501 --> 13:57.670
<i>On the outside,</i>
<i>I'm looking calm.</i>

13:57.670 --> 14:01.466
<i>I've got stone‐faced John on,</i>
<i>but inside, I'm just dying.</i>

14:01.466 --> 14:03.718
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:03.718 --> 14:06.721
<i>[tense music]</i>

14:06.721 --> 14:13.728
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:15.521 --> 14:17.690
<i>[upbeat music]</i>

14:17.690 --> 14:20.693
‐ Well, John, you lucked out.

14:20.693 --> 14:23.154
This blade took
zero damage on this test.

14:23.154 --> 14:24.989
Really well done.
‐ Thank you.

14:24.989 --> 14:26.199
‐ All right, Andrew,
you're up next.

14:26.199 --> 14:27.867
You ready?
‐ Yes sir.

14:27.867 --> 14:30.244
<i>I was confident</i>
<i>that I made parameters,</i>

14:30.244 --> 14:34.123
<i>so to hear that I didn't</i>
<i>was like a punch in the gut,</i>

14:34.123 --> 14:37.085
but I'm very happy
with my blade overall.

14:37.085 --> 14:40.213
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:40.213 --> 14:41.589
<i>[tense music]</i>

14:41.589 --> 14:43.883
<i>[rock music]</i>

14:43.883 --> 14:47.178
[clanking]

14:47.178 --> 14:51.891
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:51.891 --> 14:54.268
‐ Well, Andrew, there's
good news and bad news here.

14:54.268 --> 14:55.520
The good news
is that your edge

14:55.520 --> 14:57.563
was holding up really well.

14:57.563 --> 15:00.441
The bad news is...
your handle snapped.

15:00.441 --> 15:02.693
<i>[tense music]</i>

15:02.693 --> 15:04.487
‐ Andrew, unfortunately,

15:04.487 --> 15:07.198
you suffered a catastrophic
blade failure.

15:07.198 --> 15:09.742
Josh, your blade's up next

15:09.742 --> 15:12.578
and must survive
two licks on that nut

15:12.578 --> 15:14.789
to move forward
in this competition.

15:14.789 --> 15:17.041
Are you guys ready?
‐ No. [laughs]

15:17.041 --> 15:18.751
‐ All right.
Ben?

15:18.751 --> 15:20.211
<i>‐ At this point,</i>

15:20.211 --> 15:21.879
<i>my survival in the competition</i>

15:21.879 --> 15:24.173
<i>depends on Josh's blade</i>
<i>snapping clean in half.</i>

15:24.173 --> 15:27.135
Ah, yeah, it's just
a tough spot to be in.

15:27.135 --> 15:28.886
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:28.886 --> 15:30.805
<i>‐ If my blade doesn't hold up,</i>

15:30.805 --> 15:32.348
<i>I'm going home.</i>

15:32.348 --> 15:33.558
I feel like
I'm about to have a stroke.

15:33.558 --> 15:37.103
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

15:37.103 --> 15:40.106
<i>[rock music]</i>

15:40.106 --> 15:44.610
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:44.610 --> 15:47.655
<i>[dramatic tone]</i>

15:47.655 --> 15:49.824
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:49.824 --> 15:52.368
‐ Well, Josh, there's
no damage on this blade.

15:52.368 --> 15:53.661
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:53.661 --> 15:55.288
Very well done.
‐ Thank you.

15:56.289 --> 15:58.666
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

15:58.666 --> 16:01.210
‐ Andrew, without a tang
to attach a handle to,

16:01.210 --> 16:03.671
there's nothing to attach
the user to the blade.

16:03.671 --> 16:06.340
For that reason,
please leave The Forge.

16:06.340 --> 16:08.759
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:08.759 --> 16:11.012
‐ This did not go in my favor.

16:11.012 --> 16:12.638
First thing I do
when I get home?

16:12.638 --> 16:14.807
Probably gonna make
a bowie knife out of W1,

16:14.807 --> 16:16.267
<i>with the tang still on.</i>

16:16.267 --> 16:18.019
[laughing]

16:18.019 --> 16:20.104
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:20.104 --> 16:21.856
‐ All right, bladesmiths.

16:21.856 --> 16:24.025
It's time to turn your blades
into fully functional

16:24.025 --> 16:26.986
Rough Rider bowies
by attaching handles to them.

16:26.986 --> 16:29.989
We provided you each
with buffalo horn scales

16:29.989 --> 16:33.534
<i>from which to construct your</i>
<i>four pin coffin handle blades</i>

16:33.534 --> 16:37.371
<i>with file work liners</i>
<i>and brass guards with lobes.</i>

16:37.371 --> 16:39.707
We've added round two
to your scrolls,

16:39.707 --> 16:42.251
so there's no reason
to miss any parameters.

16:42.251 --> 16:44.170
Gentleman,
you will be happy to know

16:44.170 --> 16:47.423
that the round one parameters
are no longer in play.

16:47.423 --> 16:48.883
In this round,
you'll have three hours

16:48.883 --> 16:50.635
in which to
complete your work.

16:50.635 --> 16:52.678
After this round,
your blades will be tested

16:52.678 --> 16:55.473
for strength and durability
in a moose‐antler chop

16:55.473 --> 16:58.643
and for edge retention
in that fish slice.

16:58.643 --> 17:01.187
Good luck.
Your three hours starts now.

17:01.187 --> 17:04.607
<i>[rock music]</i>

17:04.607 --> 17:07.235
‐ Round one, I let my nerves
get the better of me.

17:07.235 --> 17:09.278
<i>Ended up coming up short</i>
<i>in two parameters,</i>

17:09.278 --> 17:11.405
and I just wasn't happy
with the overall knife.

17:11.405 --> 17:12.949
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:12.949 --> 17:13.950
<i>I know I have issues</i>
<i>with my tang.</i>

17:13.950 --> 17:15.576
<i>It's entirely too long.</i>

17:15.576 --> 17:16.786
<i>So I take it over</i>
<i>to the angle grinder,</i>

17:16.786 --> 17:18.079
<i>and I chop a big piece off.</i>

17:18.079 --> 17:20.790
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:20.790 --> 17:22.208
To get the handle length
requirements,

17:22.208 --> 17:24.085
I had to take it down
to my holes.

17:24.085 --> 17:25.878
Now I'm gonna
have to drill new holes.

17:25.878 --> 17:26.921
Yay.

17:26.921 --> 17:29.715
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:29.715 --> 17:33.302
‐ Once again, we see Dan
pulling right from the example.

17:33.302 --> 17:35.012
It did him well
in the first round.

17:35.012 --> 17:36.305
‐ He's an engineer man.

17:36.305 --> 17:37.515
He's gonna replicate
that thing

17:37.515 --> 17:39.058
to the 1/1000 of an inch.

17:39.058 --> 17:40.017
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:40.017 --> 17:41.018
<i>‐ I'm kinda worried,</i>

17:41.018 --> 17:42.562
<i>'cause we now know</i>

17:42.562 --> 17:44.272
that everyone else's blades
can survive

17:44.272 --> 17:46.357
getting bashed
into a steel bolt,

17:46.357 --> 17:49.777
and mine‐‐let's hope it can
survive a moose antler.

17:49.777 --> 17:51.946
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:51.946 --> 17:54.699
‐ I missed the parameters
for the length in round one.

17:54.699 --> 17:56.826
<i>In round two,</i>
<i>I'm not going to do</i>

17:56.826 --> 17:58.953
<i>as many flyby measurements.</i>

17:58.953 --> 18:01.664
My game plan is to thin out
my damn blade.

18:01.664 --> 18:04.625
‐ I think he's trying to drop
some of the weight out of it,

18:04.625 --> 18:07.086
get it closer
to the example, visually.

18:07.086 --> 18:09.505
I'm going to take my
time to do things right.

18:09.505 --> 18:11.507
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:11.507 --> 18:14.343
‐ Bladesmiths,
one hour has elapsed!

18:14.343 --> 18:16.095
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:16.095 --> 18:17.680
‐ I get all
the measurements drawn

18:17.680 --> 18:19.307
<i>onto my piece of brass</i>
<i>for my guard.</i>

18:19.307 --> 18:20.641
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:20.641 --> 18:22.351
<i>I drill some pilot holes</i>
<i>so that</i>

18:22.351 --> 18:24.437
<i>I know where I need</i>
<i>to get my tang through.</i>

18:24.437 --> 18:26.522
[buzzing]

18:26.522 --> 18:29.734
<i>Gotta get this thing to stay</i>
<i>on there without slipping.</i>

18:29.734 --> 18:31.819
‐ The guard that's loose,
eventually through use,

18:31.819 --> 18:33.821
it's gonna start damaging
the handle material.

18:33.821 --> 18:34.947
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:34.947 --> 18:36.699
<i>[tense music]</i>

18:36.699 --> 18:38.200
‐ I cut out the brass,
and now what I need to do

18:38.200 --> 18:41.162
is make a slot for my tang.

18:41.162 --> 18:42.413
I'm looking up at the clock,

18:42.413 --> 18:43.789
and I'm realizing
I am slowly

18:43.789 --> 18:45.666
<i>going to chew up</i>
<i>all of my time</i>

18:45.666 --> 18:48.169
<i>hand filing the guard</i>
<i>to match the tang.</i>

18:48.169 --> 18:51.005
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:51.005 --> 18:53.049
So instead, I decide‐‐

18:53.049 --> 18:54.634
I have a grinder
right in front of me.

18:54.634 --> 18:56.218
I'm going to make
the tang fit the guard.

18:56.218 --> 18:58.346
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:58.346 --> 19:01.307
‐ The coffin handle
gets thinner at the neck.

19:01.307 --> 19:04.602
It always widens towards the
back and has that coffin shape,

19:04.602 --> 19:06.437
and if you don't get
that detail,

19:06.437 --> 19:08.230
you're going to wind up
with a guard

19:08.230 --> 19:10.191
that's swimming around
on your tang.

19:10.191 --> 19:13.235
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:13.235 --> 19:16.947
‐ I have to put a guard
on this knife with lobes.

19:16.947 --> 19:19.158
My guard at the moment
is a little long.

19:19.158 --> 19:20.868
I know I need to remove
material on it.

19:20.868 --> 19:23.079
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:23.079 --> 19:25.623
I have [bleep] up my guard.

19:25.623 --> 19:28.459
‐ Uh‐oh.
John just did something wrong.

19:28.459 --> 19:30.795
‐ Oh, boy.

19:30.795 --> 19:34.090
<i>I cut off all this of material</i>
<i>on one side instead of both.</i>

19:34.090 --> 19:37.176
I don't have enough material
to make a lobe on one side.

19:37.176 --> 19:40.137
<i>I have to start all the way</i>
<i>over on this guard.</i>

19:40.137 --> 19:41.472
‐ I don't want to have
31 minutes left

19:41.472 --> 19:42.807
to make another guard

19:42.807 --> 19:44.850
and then sharpen
and glue up a handle.

19:44.850 --> 19:48.646
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:48.646 --> 19:50.231
‐ I'm grinding away
on this handle,

19:50.231 --> 19:52.191
<i>and I realize I have a gap</i>

19:52.191 --> 19:54.610
between my handle material
and my guard.

19:54.610 --> 19:56.195
Oh.

19:56.195 --> 19:58.406
My guard just came loose.

19:58.406 --> 20:00.408
<i>I have to get a pin in here.</i>

20:00.408 --> 20:02.284
<i>Hoping that, between</i>
<i>the chemical bond of the epoxy</i>

20:02.284 --> 20:03.619
<i>and the mechanical bond</i>
<i>of the pin</i>

20:03.619 --> 20:05.204
<i>it's gonna hold together.</i>

20:05.204 --> 20:06.372
‐ Wow, that's not
very thick brass

20:06.372 --> 20:07.456
to be drilling through.

20:07.456 --> 20:09.875
‐ I've got epoxy everywhere.

20:09.875 --> 20:11.127
Yep.

20:11.127 --> 20:12.211
<i>Thankfully, it's in the gap</i>

20:12.211 --> 20:13.796
<i>where I need it to be.</i>

20:13.796 --> 20:15.172
I'm done.
I'm gonna step back from it.

20:15.172 --> 20:16.382
That's‐‐it is what it is.

20:16.382 --> 20:17.758
That's all I can do to it.

20:17.758 --> 20:19.343
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:19.343 --> 20:21.470
‐ Watching Dan over here,
and he's falling behind,

20:21.470 --> 20:24.181
because he's so precise,
but you know what?

20:24.181 --> 20:26.100
This is a competition
about precision.

20:26.100 --> 20:27.309
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:27.309 --> 20:28.477
‐ I need to put some decorative

20:28.477 --> 20:30.479
file work on the brass liners.

20:30.479 --> 20:32.606
‐ Dan is, uh, just going
at his file work

20:32.606 --> 20:34.108
with that Dremel.

20:34.108 --> 20:35.776
‐ Now I need to start gluing

20:35.776 --> 20:37.778
all of my pieces
together.

20:37.778 --> 20:40.197
I realize I have 15 minutes

20:40.197 --> 20:43.075
to put an edge on my blade
and to shape the handle.

20:43.075 --> 20:46.996
I'm relying on it to be curing
while I'm sharpening my blade,

20:46.996 --> 20:48.330
<i>but that clock is ticking,</i>
<i>and I might not</i>

20:48.330 --> 20:49.623
<i>have enough time to finish.</i>

20:49.623 --> 20:51.167
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:51.167 --> 20:53.377
<i>[rock music]</i>

20:53.377 --> 20:57.256
‐ I need to get this new
guard done and finished now.

20:57.256 --> 20:59.091
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:59.091 --> 21:00.468
Okay.

21:00.468 --> 21:02.595
I don't have the time,
and I'm rushing.

21:02.595 --> 21:05.723
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:05.723 --> 21:08.184
Everything has just now
gotten epoxied and cured,

21:08.184 --> 21:10.352
and there are problems.

21:10.352 --> 21:11.520
<i>My guard isn't shaped,</i>

21:11.520 --> 21:13.022
<i>I don't have these lobes,</i>

21:13.022 --> 21:14.648
<i>it's probably</i>
<i>still too long...</i>

21:14.648 --> 21:16.108
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:16.108 --> 21:17.902
<i>So I have to go</i>
<i>to the grinder,</i>

21:17.902 --> 21:19.487
<i>roughen these lobes,</i>

21:19.487 --> 21:21.781
and then roughen the handle.

21:21.781 --> 21:24.200
<i>It doesn't look exactly like</i>
<i>the Rough Rider bowie,</i>

21:24.200 --> 21:26.494
<i>and it's a replication</i>
<i>challenge.</i>

21:26.494 --> 21:29.330
I'm kind of shaking in my
boots at this point about it.

21:29.330 --> 21:30.873
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:30.873 --> 21:36.045
‐ Five. Four. Three. Two. One.

21:36.045 --> 21:37.922
Bladesmiths,
drop your tools.

21:37.922 --> 21:39.381
Stop what you're doing.

21:39.381 --> 21:42.802
This second round
of competition is over.

21:42.802 --> 21:44.303
<i>‐ I'm looking</i>
<i>at my competitors' blades,</i>

21:44.303 --> 21:46.055
<i>and mine just doesn't</i>
<i>look as pretty.</i>

21:46.055 --> 21:47.973
<i>I'm hoping that it will</i>
<i>outperform theirs,</i>

21:47.973 --> 21:49.975
and maybe looks
will come second.

21:49.975 --> 21:52.353
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:52.353 --> 21:54.271
‐ Bladesmiths, welcome
to the strength test.

21:54.271 --> 21:55.815
The moose‐antler chop.

21:55.815 --> 21:57.441
Remember,
this test is all about

21:57.441 --> 21:59.026
what the antler
does to your bowies

21:59.026 --> 22:00.194
and not what
the Rough Rider bowies

22:00.194 --> 22:03.072
do to these moose antlers.

22:03.072 --> 22:04.323
Dan, you're up first.
Are you ready?

22:04.323 --> 22:06.033
‐ Yes, sir.
‐ All right.

22:06.033 --> 22:08.285
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:08.285 --> 22:09.954
<i>‐ I'm really worried about</i>
<i>the moose‐antler chop,</i>

22:09.954 --> 22:11.956
<i>because it's such a brittle,</i>
<i>hard material,</i>

22:11.956 --> 22:14.875
and it can crack or dent
an edge very, very easily.

22:14.875 --> 22:19.046
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:19.046 --> 22:21.966
[banging]

22:21.966 --> 22:25.886
<i>[rock music]</i>

22:25.886 --> 22:32.893
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:32.893 --> 22:34.395
‐ Well, Dan,
first thing's first.

22:34.395 --> 22:35.813
This edge held up perfectly.

22:35.813 --> 22:38.482
There's no plinting,
rolling, chipping.

22:38.482 --> 22:41.110
One small issue‐‐there's
a little piece of the handle

22:41.110 --> 22:43.529
that comes up right here,
and it's sharp.

22:43.529 --> 22:44.738
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:44.738 --> 22:46.490
In general, really well done.

22:46.490 --> 22:47.825
‐ Thank you.

22:47.825 --> 22:48.993
‐ John, you're up.
You ready?

22:48.993 --> 22:51.120
‐ Yes, sir.

22:51.120 --> 22:52.621
<i>There are gaps in my handle,</i>

22:52.621 --> 22:55.124
<i>and that could pose</i>
<i>some issues.</i>

22:55.124 --> 22:56.709
In the back of my mind,
I'm thinking

22:56.709 --> 22:58.586
<i>that the handle</i>
<i>could just fly apart.</i>

22:58.586 --> 23:03.257
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:03.257 --> 23:07.052
[banging]

23:07.052 --> 23:10.055
<i>[rock music]</i>

23:10.055 --> 23:15.269
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:15.269 --> 23:17.021
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

23:17.021 --> 23:18.355
‐ Well, John,
a couple things happened.

23:18.355 --> 23:19.648
First and foremost,

23:19.648 --> 23:21.859
your guard is‐‐is quite loose.

23:21.859 --> 23:25.613
In the testing,
your edge took a roll...

23:25.613 --> 23:26.989
[clicking]
That you can hear here.

23:26.989 --> 23:28.866
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:28.866 --> 23:30.492
In all, I mean, it's‐‐

23:30.492 --> 23:32.161
it's one knife instead of two,
which is great,

23:32.161 --> 23:34.413
and it's got a great
look to it, so well done.

23:34.413 --> 23:35.956
‐ Thank you, sir.

23:35.956 --> 23:37.416
‐ Josh.

23:37.416 --> 23:38.542
You're up.
You ready?

23:38.542 --> 23:40.002
‐ Does it matter?

23:40.002 --> 23:42.796
‐ No.
‐ Okay.

23:42.796 --> 23:45.132
<i>So they tested Dan's blade.</i>
<i>They tested John's.</i>

23:45.132 --> 23:46.675
<i>John's took a little</i>
<i>bit of damage,</i>

23:46.675 --> 23:49.803
<i>but nothing</i>
<i>that was catastrophic.</i>

23:49.803 --> 23:52.640
Now they're on to mine,
and I'm worried.

23:52.640 --> 23:55.768
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:55.768 --> 23:58.479
<i>[rock music]</i>

23:58.479 --> 24:01.482
[banging]

24:01.482 --> 24:04.401
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:04.401 --> 24:05.569
[exhales slowly]

24:05.569 --> 24:06.570
‐ [whispers]
Good job, man.

24:06.570 --> 24:08.197
‐ Thanks.

24:08.197 --> 24:09.782
‐ Well, Josh,
first thing's first.

24:09.782 --> 24:12.660
There are some serious gaps
on both sides

24:12.660 --> 24:14.370
between the handle material
and the guard.

24:14.370 --> 24:17.373
Aside from those issues,
the blade held up perfectly.

24:17.373 --> 24:18.540
Well done.

24:18.540 --> 24:19.917
‐ Thank you.

24:19.917 --> 24:22.878
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

24:22.878 --> 24:24.505
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:24.505 --> 24:26.465
‐ Bladesmiths,
welcome to the sharpness test:

24:26.465 --> 24:28.050
the fish slice.

24:28.050 --> 24:31.011
To find out if there's
any edge left to your weapon,

24:31.011 --> 24:32.596
I'm going to take your
Rough Rider bowies

24:32.596 --> 24:35.849
and try to get some
salmon steaks out of this fish.

24:35.849 --> 24:37.726
Dan, you're up first.
You ready?

24:37.726 --> 24:39.311
‐ Yes, sir.
‐ Let's do this.

24:39.311 --> 24:42.314
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

24:42.314 --> 24:46.318
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:46.318 --> 24:47.319
[whoosh]

24:47.319 --> 24:51.073
<i>[music builds]</i>

24:51.073 --> 24:54.034
<i>[rock music]</i>

24:54.034 --> 24:57.371
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:57.371 --> 24:58.372
[squelching]

24:58.372 --> 25:01.208
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:01.208 --> 25:03.502
[squelching]

25:04.628 --> 25:07.464
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

25:07.464 --> 25:10.009
‐ Well, we got
four steaks out of it.

25:10.009 --> 25:11.385
Beautiful job.

25:11.385 --> 25:13.137
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:13.137 --> 25:14.680
It is sharp.

25:14.680 --> 25:16.098
There was a spot
here on the guard

25:16.098 --> 25:17.933
that could have been
smoothened out,

25:17.933 --> 25:19.935
but it did not affect
the use of your blade.

25:19.935 --> 25:21.520
The balance
of your blade is good,

25:21.520 --> 25:23.814
and most importantly,
it will cut.

25:23.814 --> 25:25.357
Good job, sir.
‐ Thank you.

25:25.357 --> 25:27.234
‐ John, you ready?
‐ Yes, sir.

25:27.234 --> 25:30.571
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

25:30.571 --> 25:37.536
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:43.292 --> 25:50.340
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:51.550 --> 25:53.052
‐ All right, John,
let's talk about

25:53.052 --> 25:55.262
your Rough Rider bowie
right here.

25:55.262 --> 25:56.764
First up, on the first cut,

25:56.764 --> 25:58.640
it didn't cut
all the way through.

25:58.640 --> 26:00.309
I just ran out of blade,

26:00.309 --> 26:02.936
but on the subsequent cuts,
it is sharp,

26:02.936 --> 26:04.605
and overall, sir,

26:04.605 --> 26:06.857
your blade, it will cut.

26:06.857 --> 26:08.358
‐ Thank you, sir.

26:08.358 --> 26:09.860
‐ All right, Josh.
Your turn. You ready?

26:09.860 --> 26:11.445
‐ Do it to it.
‐ Let's do it.

26:11.445 --> 26:15.616
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:15.616 --> 26:16.575
‐ [exhales]

26:16.575 --> 26:19.620
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

26:19.620 --> 26:24.124
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:24.124 --> 26:25.125
[squelches]

26:25.125 --> 26:32.091
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:35.344 --> 26:36.720
‐ [whispers] Good job.
‐ [whispers] Thanks, man.

26:36.720 --> 26:38.764
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

26:38.764 --> 26:40.015
‐ All right, Josh.

26:40.015 --> 26:41.225
Let's talk about
your blade here.

26:41.225 --> 26:43.685
First up is the handle.

26:43.685 --> 26:45.395
It feels like it should
be held this way,

26:45.395 --> 26:47.106
because it's off line,

26:47.106 --> 26:48.899
and in one of the cuts,

26:48.899 --> 26:51.527
it did affect the way
I was indexing.

26:51.527 --> 26:54.029
My hip, with the guard,
and then into the blade.

26:54.029 --> 26:57.991
But this is a sharp blade,
and it will cut.

26:57.991 --> 26:59.451
‐ That's awesome.
That's all I wanted to hear.

26:59.451 --> 27:00.828
[laughs]

27:00.828 --> 27:02.162
‐ Bladesmiths, we asked you

27:02.162 --> 27:03.664
to make Rough Rider bowies

27:03.664 --> 27:06.041
to honor President
Theodore Roosevelt.

27:06.041 --> 27:07.543
The judges' deliberation
is complete.

27:07.543 --> 27:09.044
They've made a final decision.

27:09.044 --> 27:11.338
Only two of you can move
forward into the finale.

27:11.338 --> 27:14.967
One of you bladesmiths
has to leave The Forge,

27:14.967 --> 27:16.677
and that bladesmith is...

27:16.677 --> 27:19.096
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:24.268 --> 27:25.227
[hammJohn.anks]

27:25.227 --> 27:26.854
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:26.854 --> 27:28.313
Your blade didn't make the cut.

27:28.313 --> 27:30.732
David Baker's
gonna tell you why.

27:30.732 --> 27:33.026
‐ John, this decision
came down to the strength test,

27:33.026 --> 27:34.736
in which your blade
picked up a rolled edge

27:34.736 --> 27:36.530
<i>and a loose guard,</i>

27:36.530 --> 27:38.407
making it the only blade
that took any damage.

27:38.407 --> 27:39.825
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:39.825 --> 27:42.077
‐ John, please surrender
your bowie.

27:42.077 --> 27:44.913
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:44.913 --> 27:46.373
‐ My only real regret is that

27:46.373 --> 27:47.583
<i>the handle</i>
<i>just didn't hold up.</i>

27:47.583 --> 27:49.126
<i>The guard didn't hold up.</i>

27:49.126 --> 27:51.044
I would have worked better
on the handle.

27:51.044 --> 27:53.297
<i>I came here</i>
<i>to prove to myself that</i>

27:53.297 --> 27:56.341
I am working down the right
path of my craftsmanship,

27:56.341 --> 27:58.468
and I believe
I've proved that to myself

27:58.468 --> 28:00.178
under these conditions.

28:00.178 --> 28:03.140
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:03.140 --> 28:04.683
‐ Dan, Josh, congratulations.

28:04.683 --> 28:06.184
You fellas have made it

28:06.184 --> 28:07.769
into the final round
of this competition.

28:07.769 --> 28:09.479
We're gonna send you
back to your home forge

28:09.479 --> 28:11.273
to recreate an iconic

28:11.273 --> 28:13.483
presidential weapon
from history.

28:13.483 --> 28:14.610
That weapon is...

28:14.610 --> 28:17.112
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:17.112 --> 28:20.198
George Washington's
colichemarde.

28:20.198 --> 28:21.199
<i>‐ I've never even heard</i>
<i>of this thing.</i>

28:21.199 --> 28:22.576
<i>Never seen it, nothing.</i>

28:22.576 --> 28:24.119
Right now,
my heart is just racing

28:24.119 --> 28:25.829
<i>'cause I'm freaking out.</i>

28:25.829 --> 28:27.706
<i>‐ The colichemarde</i>
<i>was a unique dueling sword</i>

28:27.706 --> 28:30.709
<i>that became popular during</i>
<i>the late 17th century</i>

28:30.709 --> 28:33.754
<i>and was a favorite blade</i>
<i>style of George Washington.</i>

28:33.754 --> 28:35.923
<i>The weapon had</i>
<i>an extremely broad forte,</i>

28:35.923 --> 28:38.216
<i>which gave the blade</i>
<i>ample parrying strength.</i>

28:38.216 --> 28:41.470
<i>However, the sword rapidly</i>
<i>tapered to a thin point,</i>

28:41.470 --> 28:44.890
<i>allowing for precise thrusting</i>
<i>and stabbing attacks.</i>

28:44.890 --> 28:47.309
<i>An avid sword collector,</i>
<i>George Washington</i>

28:47.309 --> 28:50.562
<i>even had a colichemarde</i>
<i>bladed small sword at his side</i>

28:50.562 --> 28:53.148
<i>while swearing in</i>
<i>as America's first president.</i>

28:53.148 --> 28:56.151
<i>The weapon was such an iconic</i>
<i>part of Washington's persona,</i>

28:56.151 --> 28:58.987
<i>one can even be spotted</i>
<i>alongside the first president</i>

28:58.987 --> 29:02.824
<i>in this iconic 1824</i>
<i>John Trumbull painting.</i>

29:02.824 --> 29:04.576
Your blades must fall

29:04.576 --> 29:05.786
within the following
parameters.

29:05.786 --> 29:07.079
Your blade must be

29:07.079 --> 29:09.456
between 31 and 33 inches
in length.

29:09.456 --> 29:12.918
This is a unique
tri‐foil blade design

29:12.918 --> 29:14.920
with a forte
that must be between

29:14.920 --> 29:16.964
9 and 12 inches in length.

29:16.964 --> 29:20.509
Your handle must include
a pommel, a knuckle‐bow,

29:20.509 --> 29:23.762
and a perforated,
decorated oval guard.

29:23.762 --> 29:26.056
Bladesmiths, you'll have
five days at your home forges

29:26.056 --> 29:27.849
in which to complete
this blade.

29:27.849 --> 29:29.893
At the end of those
five days, you will return

29:29.893 --> 29:32.479
and present your weapons
to our panel of expert judges,

29:32.479 --> 29:34.398
and only after they've
thoroughly tested them

29:34.398 --> 29:37.025
will they declare one of you
the "Forged in Fire" champion,

29:37.025 --> 29:41.196
who also leaves here
with a check for $10,000.

29:41.196 --> 29:44.032
Good luck.
We'll see you in five days.

29:44.032 --> 29:47.869
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:47.869 --> 29:51.415
‐ It feels real good to be back
home in my normal shop.

29:51.415 --> 29:53.250
Get my thinking cap on.

29:53.250 --> 29:56.378
<i>My biggest concern is figuring</i>
<i>out that tri‐foil blade.</i>

29:56.378 --> 29:58.672
It's definitely the most
intricate sword I've ever made.

29:58.672 --> 30:02.342
But I'm confident that
I can redneck engineer it.

30:02.342 --> 30:03.427
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:03.427 --> 30:05.012
<i>I'm about four inches</i>

30:05.012 --> 30:07.097
<i>into putting</i>
<i>this tri‐fold in there,</i>

30:07.097 --> 30:11.018
<i>and I realize that instead of</i>
<i>wavering off back and forth,</i>

30:11.018 --> 30:13.270
I need to just cut
a small groove

30:13.270 --> 30:14.980
on the line where I need to go

30:14.980 --> 30:17.232
<i>that will keep it</i>
<i>where it needs to be.</i>

30:17.232 --> 30:18.734
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:18.734 --> 30:20.610
<i>So now that I have</i>
<i>a guideline cut,</i>

30:20.610 --> 30:22.279
<i>Trifold's coming along</i>
<i>more in a straight line,</i>

30:22.279 --> 30:23.613
<i>like it needs to be.</i>

30:23.613 --> 30:25.574
So far, things are going

30:25.574 --> 30:27.743
about 98% the way
I intended for 'em to go.

30:27.743 --> 30:33.123
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:33.123 --> 30:35.208
<i>‐ It's the final,</i>
<i>so I'm back at my home forge.</i>

30:35.208 --> 30:36.668
There's 10 grand on the line.

30:36.668 --> 30:37.961
<i>My pride too.</i>

30:37.961 --> 30:39.379
<i>This is a big deal.</i>

30:39.379 --> 30:41.465
Day one, I'm starting up
the forge.

30:41.465 --> 30:43.383
Time to get hot and heavy.

30:43.383 --> 30:46.053
So my plan is to actually
make a Damascus billet

30:46.053 --> 30:47.054
to use for the hand guard.

30:47.054 --> 30:48.221
14, 15, 16, 17,

30:48.221 --> 30:50.974
18, 19, 20, 21 layers.

30:50.974 --> 30:52.893
<i>You know, I don't have to do</i>
<i>this as part of the challenge,</i>

30:52.893 --> 30:56.480
but I need to find some way to
edge out against my competitor.

30:56.480 --> 30:58.106
Ah, [bleep].

30:58.106 --> 30:59.608
[rumbling]

30:59.608 --> 31:01.193
I am out of propane.

31:01.193 --> 31:02.903
I'm, uh, pretty pissed off.

31:02.903 --> 31:06.448
It's a rookie mistake
that should not have happened.

31:06.448 --> 31:09.409
That means that now I've got to
run out and grab propane.

31:09.409 --> 31:11.203
It's at least an hour's
worth of time,

31:11.203 --> 31:14.873
<i>and it's a real [bleep] way</i>
<i>to start this off.</i>

31:14.873 --> 31:17.459
<i>I need to make up for</i>
<i>a whole lot of lost time.</i>

31:17.459 --> 31:19.419
An hour can make or break it.

31:19.419 --> 31:21.838
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:21.838 --> 31:25.175
<i>‐ Day two, I've got to get</i>
<i>my blade finished out</i>

31:25.175 --> 31:27.636
<i>with forging as much as I can.</i>

31:27.636 --> 31:29.721
<i>Historically,</i>
<i>it's a very light sword,</i>

31:29.721 --> 31:32.599
and right now,
I'm at about three pounds.

31:32.599 --> 31:35.227
Gonna have to put this
on a diet, real quick.

31:35.227 --> 31:36.853
<i>Hopefully I can</i>
<i>get it down to, like,</i>

31:36.853 --> 31:38.396
<i>pound and a half to a pound.</i>

31:38.396 --> 31:40.607
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:40.607 --> 31:41.817
[bleep] kidding me.

31:41.817 --> 31:43.318
I ground through right there.

31:43.318 --> 31:45.237
I can see daylight through it.

31:45.237 --> 31:47.072
<i>Tried to MIG weld it,</i>

31:47.072 --> 31:49.908
<i>and it immediately</i>
<i>just melts the whole thing.</i>

31:49.908 --> 31:51.576
Big ass hole right there.

31:55.163 --> 31:58.208
<i>‐ Worked for 15 hours on this</i>
<i>blade, and now it's garbage.</i>

31:58.208 --> 32:00.418
I can't fix it.

32:00.418 --> 32:03.046
<i>I have to start all over.</i>

32:03.046 --> 32:04.923
<i>Two or three more minutes</i>
<i>left in day two,</i>

32:04.923 --> 32:08.426
and I've kind of got
the tip forged.

32:08.426 --> 32:10.220
It is what it is.

32:10.220 --> 32:13.390
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:13.390 --> 32:15.267
‐ Day three,
I'm doing pretty good.

32:15.267 --> 32:17.936
<i>I'm profiling my blade</i>
<i>with a grinder.</i>

32:17.936 --> 32:19.437
[machine winds down]

32:19.437 --> 32:20.981
The hell?

32:20.981 --> 32:22.357
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:22.357 --> 32:23.567
<i>And all of the sudden,</i>

32:23.567 --> 32:25.986
grinder shuts off.

32:25.986 --> 32:26.987
<i>I start blowing it out.</i>

32:26.987 --> 32:27.946
[pop]

32:27.946 --> 32:29.447
Ah, [bleep].

32:29.447 --> 32:31.700
<i>One piece of equipment</i>
<i>in my shop</i>

32:31.700 --> 32:34.661
<i>that is irreplaceable</i>
<i>is now on fire.</i>

32:34.661 --> 32:36.788
I don't have a grinder.

32:36.788 --> 32:38.373
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:38.373 --> 32:39.916
<i>The only thing</i>
<i>I can do now‐‐</i>

32:39.916 --> 32:41.710
<i>and it still</i>
<i>isn't a guarantee‐‐</i>

32:41.710 --> 32:43.628
<i>is drive all the way back</i>
<i>to the hardware store</i>

32:43.628 --> 32:44.921
and get a single‐phase motor.

32:44.921 --> 32:47.465
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:47.465 --> 32:49.634
New motor to replace
the one that fried.

32:49.634 --> 32:51.386
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:51.386 --> 32:53.930
All right, so this
is the moment of truth.

32:53.930 --> 32:55.807
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:55.807 --> 32:56.933
[whirring]

32:56.933 --> 32:58.476
We are back up and running!

32:58.476 --> 33:00.312
Hell, yeah!

33:00.312 --> 33:02.606
<i>This metal is moving so well</i>

33:02.606 --> 33:05.734
that I'm breezing past this.

33:05.734 --> 33:08.653
<i>[rock music]</i>

33:08.653 --> 33:11.990
<i>‐ 24 hours ago, I had</i>
<i>that blade in two pieces.</i>

33:11.990 --> 33:15.327
<i>I am extremely happy</i>
<i>that the blade is done.</i>

33:15.327 --> 33:17.621
So I can focus on
the guard assembly,

33:17.621 --> 33:19.247
the handle, and the pommel.

33:19.247 --> 33:20.832
<i>So, for the pommel,</i>
<i>I'm actually using</i>

33:20.832 --> 33:23.627
<i>a piece of muzzle loader</i>
<i>rifle barrel.</i>

33:23.627 --> 33:26.254
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:26.254 --> 33:28.131
<i>For the handle,</i>
<i>I'm gonna use bubinga,</i>

33:28.131 --> 33:30.258
<i>which is like</i>
<i>a tropical hardwood,</i>

33:30.258 --> 33:32.010
<i>but it's super light.</i>

33:32.010 --> 33:33.845
Do a little work there too.

33:33.845 --> 33:35.513
If you told me,
at the end of day two,

33:35.513 --> 33:36.848
<i>that I was gonna</i>
<i>be where I'm at now,</i>

33:36.848 --> 33:38.308
I wouldn't have believed you.

33:38.308 --> 33:39.643
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:39.643 --> 33:40.977
Day four.

33:40.977 --> 33:43.521
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:43.521 --> 33:45.690
<i>‐ Today is day five.</i>

33:45.690 --> 33:49.194
I've got, like, a list
of over‐the‐top optional stuff

33:49.194 --> 33:51.404
<i>that I'm gonna do</i>
<i>if I have the time to do it.</i>

33:51.404 --> 33:53.156
Here we go.
It's good.

33:53.156 --> 33:55.200
So I'm pretty
confident about time.

33:55.200 --> 33:57.035
I've got a good portion
of the day left,

33:57.035 --> 33:59.162
<i>so I'm gonna make</i>
<i>some last‐minute</i>

33:59.162 --> 34:00.664
mokume for the pommel.

34:00.664 --> 34:03.041
<i>I've got some really</i>
<i>great mokume</i>

34:03.041 --> 34:05.001
at the top of the guard,
and a part of me

34:05.001 --> 34:07.337
just needs to see
a little bit of balance.

34:07.337 --> 34:09.464
<i>So this is absolutely</i>
<i>a design decision,</i>

34:09.464 --> 34:12.884
<i>but I‐‐I'm looking at this,</i>
<i>and I really want to do it.</i>

34:12.884 --> 34:15.428
So something
that I was gonna do extra,

34:15.428 --> 34:17.013
just to put the icing
on the cake,

34:17.013 --> 34:19.057
is now gonna eat into time.

34:19.057 --> 34:20.558
Clock is ticking down,

34:20.558 --> 34:22.352
<i>and the only thing</i>
<i>I keep thinking</i>

34:22.352 --> 34:24.396
<i>is there's not an edge</i>
<i>on this yet.</i>

34:24.396 --> 34:26.356
<i>There's not an edge</i>
<i>on this yet.</i>

34:26.356 --> 34:27.899
<i>I didn't leave myself, really,</i>

34:27.899 --> 34:30.068
<i>a good amount of time</i>
<i>to sharpen.</i>

34:30.068 --> 34:32.320
Didn't have a good chance
to do one over

34:32.320 --> 34:34.322
and look at stuff,
but it is what it is.

34:34.322 --> 34:37.075
It's a rough sharp,
but it'll kill somebody.

34:37.075 --> 34:38.994
Washington's colichemarde.

34:38.994 --> 34:42.038
<i>[tense music]</i>

34:42.038 --> 34:44.582
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:44.582 --> 34:47.419
‐ Dan, Josh,
welcome back to The Forge.

34:47.419 --> 34:49.254
Dan, tell me about your blade.

34:50.255 --> 34:52.924
<i>‐ My colichemarde</i>
<i>is made out of 80CRV2.</i>

34:52.924 --> 34:54.426
<i>The guard is made</i>
<i>out of Damascus,</i>

34:54.426 --> 34:56.219
<i>and I used a mokume gane</i>

34:56.219 --> 34:58.763
<i>on both the pommel</i>
<i>and on the shield on top.</i>

34:58.763 --> 35:01.391
‐ How did it go for you, Josh?

35:01.391 --> 35:03.435
<i>‐ That is 5160</i>

35:03.435 --> 35:05.729
<i>with part of a rifle barrel</i>
<i>for the pommel,</i>

35:05.729 --> 35:09.065
<i>and everything else is just</i>
<i>mild steel for the guard.</i>

35:09.065 --> 35:10.358
‐ All right, gentlemen.

35:10.358 --> 35:11.610
Your weapons
will now be put through

35:11.610 --> 35:13.111
a series of three tests.

35:13.111 --> 35:15.113
Up first, the kill test.

35:15.113 --> 35:16.323
Doug?

35:16.323 --> 35:17.449
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:17.449 --> 35:18.867
‐ To find out what kind

35:18.867 --> 35:20.785
of lethal damage
your weapon will do,

35:20.785 --> 35:22.120
I will take your colichemarde

35:22.120 --> 35:23.747
and deliver harassing
cuts and thrusts

35:23.747 --> 35:25.123
to this pig carcass.

35:25.123 --> 35:26.750
Josh, you're up first.
You ready?

35:26.750 --> 35:28.084
‐ Not really, but go ahead.

35:28.084 --> 35:31.630
Pig carcasses are not soft
material.

35:31.630 --> 35:33.465
<i>They are very hard</i>
<i>to cut through,</i>

35:33.465 --> 35:36.509
so my knees feel like they're
gonna turn inside‐out on me,

35:36.509 --> 35:38.678
<i>and just‐‐yeah,</i>
<i>it's craziness.</i>

35:38.678 --> 35:42.307
<i>[intense music]</i>

35:42.307 --> 35:45.935
[thwacking]

35:45.935 --> 35:52.942
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:57.447 --> 36:03.119
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:03.119 --> 36:05.330
[exhales]
<i>‐</i> All right, Josh.

36:05.330 --> 36:07.666
First off, it's got
nice weight to it.

36:07.666 --> 36:09.167
Now, your handle construction‐‐

36:09.167 --> 36:11.211
it is small enough

36:11.211 --> 36:12.545
to where I can get my hand
around it,

36:12.545 --> 36:14.047
but it doesn't roll.

36:14.047 --> 36:17.676
Your edge,
as you can see, is sharp.

36:17.676 --> 36:20.220
It will kill.
‐ Thank you, sir.

36:20.220 --> 36:21.638
‐ All right, Dan.
It's your turn.

36:21.638 --> 36:22.889
You ready for this?
‐ Let's do it.

36:22.889 --> 36:25.642
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

36:25.642 --> 36:27.394
[exhales]

36:27.394 --> 36:28.687
<i>[music builds]</i>

36:28.687 --> 36:31.690
<i>[rock music]</i>

36:31.690 --> 36:34.651
[thwacking]

36:34.651 --> 36:41.616
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:43.868 --> 36:44.869
[squelches]

36:44.869 --> 36:51.876
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:55.839 --> 36:57.716
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

36:57.716 --> 37:01.219
‐ All right, Dan.
You have a very aggressive tip.

37:01.219 --> 37:03.722
The thrusting worked very well,

37:03.722 --> 37:06.891
but your edges right here
are not sharp.

37:06.891 --> 37:09.602
I mean, I can even
move it around with my glove.

37:09.602 --> 37:10.895
It's not cutting it.

37:10.895 --> 37:14.399
You can see that
your blade took a bend.

37:14.399 --> 37:16.276
But overall, because
you're able to thrust,

37:16.276 --> 37:18.528
this blade, sir, will kill.

37:18.528 --> 37:20.155
‐ Thank you.

37:21.740 --> 37:22.741
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:22.741 --> 37:24.075
‐ All right, gentlemen.

37:24.075 --> 37:25.243
It's time for
the strength test:

37:25.243 --> 37:27.036
our cherry wood chop,

37:27.036 --> 37:29.247
in honor
of George Washington.

37:29.247 --> 37:30.498
The colichemarde was known

37:30.498 --> 37:33.209
as a fast, light,
flexible weapon.

37:33.209 --> 37:34.753
It was designed for the duel.

37:34.753 --> 37:36.921
So, to test the strength
of your blade,

37:36.921 --> 37:39.340
I'll be doing several
tip cuts against that wood

37:39.340 --> 37:40.717
and then thrusting into it,

37:40.717 --> 37:42.635
flexing your blade
in both directions.

37:42.635 --> 37:44.053
Make sure that tempers right

37:44.053 --> 37:46.181
and that that blade
doesn't pick up a set.

37:46.181 --> 37:47.557
Josh, you're up first.
Are you ready?

37:47.557 --> 37:49.434
‐ Go for it.

37:49.434 --> 37:52.437
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

37:52.437 --> 37:58.610
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:58.610 --> 38:02.071
[clanking]

38:02.071 --> 38:09.078
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:16.461 --> 38:18.004
<i>[tense music]</i>

38:18.004 --> 38:19.464
‐ All right, Josh.

38:19.464 --> 38:21.716
There are a lot of pointy
bits on this guard

38:21.716 --> 38:23.092
that don't need to be there.

38:23.092 --> 38:26.137
That really digs
right into your hand.

38:26.137 --> 38:28.097
Other than that, you did well.

38:28.097 --> 38:29.390
It flexed very nicely

38:29.390 --> 38:31.643
and came back to true,
so good job.

38:31.643 --> 38:32.894
‐ Thank you.

38:34.979 --> 38:36.523
‐ All right, Dan.
Are you ready to go?

38:36.523 --> 38:38.233
‐ Sure, let's go.

38:38.233 --> 38:43.822
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

38:43.822 --> 38:47.826
[clanking]

38:47.826 --> 38:54.791
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:54.791 --> 38:57.794
[metal creaking]

38:59.420 --> 39:02.799
[indistinct whispering]

39:04.217 --> 39:06.511
‐ [mouthing]

39:06.511 --> 39:08.346
‐ I commend your‐‐your effort

39:08.346 --> 39:12.183
in making a blade that's‐‐
that's very nicely done,

39:12.183 --> 39:16.271
but the heat treat on
this blade has just failed.

39:16.271 --> 39:18.189
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:18.189 --> 39:20.900
I mean, I no longer
know where the tip is,

39:20.900 --> 39:22.694
which is disappointing,

39:22.694 --> 39:24.487
because I think you did
a beautiful job

39:24.487 --> 39:25.738
constructing this weapon.

39:25.738 --> 39:27.031
‐ Mm.

39:27.031 --> 39:30.076
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:30.076 --> 39:31.369
‐ All right, bladesmiths.

39:31.369 --> 39:33.371
To find out how sharp
your weapons are,

39:33.371 --> 39:35.039
I will take a colichemarde
and deliver

39:35.039 --> 39:38.084
harassing slashes and thrusts
on these sandbags.

39:38.084 --> 39:39.294
Josh, you're up first.
You ready for this?

39:39.294 --> 39:40.461
‐ Sure.

39:40.461 --> 39:43.464
<i>[rock music]</i>

39:43.464 --> 39:49.846
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:49.846 --> 39:52.223
[clanks]

39:52.223 --> 39:59.230
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:00.732 --> 40:02.901
[clanking]

40:02.901 --> 40:04.736
‐ [grunts]

40:04.736 --> 40:11.743
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:13.828 --> 40:16.247
[sand pattering]

40:20.460 --> 40:21.461
All right, Josh.

40:21.461 --> 40:23.713
Once again, very sharp edge

40:23.713 --> 40:25.006
on your blade right here.

40:25.006 --> 40:27.425
Easily cut through
these sandbags.

40:27.425 --> 40:30.094
It stayed true,
easy to align

40:30.094 --> 40:31.763
and see my target and cut it,

40:31.763 --> 40:33.806
and it will cut.

40:33.806 --> 40:34.891
‐ Thank you.

40:34.891 --> 40:35.934
‐ Dan, you ready?

40:35.934 --> 40:37.101
‐ Yup.

40:37.101 --> 40:38.561
‐ Let's do this.

40:38.561 --> 40:41.606
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

40:41.606 --> 40:48.571
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:53.952 --> 40:57.622
Dan, when I look at
the bend on this colichemarde,

40:57.622 --> 40:59.958
I won't be able to stab
straight and true.

40:59.958 --> 41:01.793
I won't really know
where the tip is,

41:01.793 --> 41:03.503
and for me,
that's a real problem.

41:03.503 --> 41:06.130
I don't feel like
I can test this blade

41:06.130 --> 41:08.841
in the same way I can test
the blade before it,

41:08.841 --> 41:10.969
because if I have to do
any kind of corrections,

41:10.969 --> 41:13.805
that's not a fair test.

41:13.805 --> 41:15.223
‐ Unfortunately, Dan,

41:15.223 --> 41:17.183
your blade did not
make the cut,

41:17.183 --> 41:18.601
and for that reason,
I have to ask you

41:18.601 --> 41:20.937
to please leave The Forge.

41:20.937 --> 41:22.814
<i>‐ As, you know, like,</i>
<i>a period piece,</i>

41:22.814 --> 41:25.316
<i>as a wall hanger,</i>
<i>my blade was spot‐on,</i>

41:25.316 --> 41:27.902
but as a sword,
it just didn't make the cut.

41:27.902 --> 41:30.947
Leaving this,
I feel like I learned more

41:30.947 --> 41:33.324
<i>than a lot of other</i>
<i>times in my life,</i>

41:33.324 --> 41:35.743
and I finished a better smith
than I was before,

41:35.743 --> 41:37.495
and really, that's the best
I could hope for.

41:37.495 --> 41:39.622
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:39.622 --> 41:42.166
‐ Josh, you are the new
"Forged in Fire" champion,

41:42.166 --> 41:46.671
and that is a title that
comes with a check for $10,000.

41:46.671 --> 41:47.714
Good job.

41:47.714 --> 41:48.798
[applause]

41:48.798 --> 41:50.174
<i>‐ This is, hands down,</i>

41:50.174 --> 41:51.676
one of the best moments
of my life.

41:51.676 --> 41:52.885
‐ Good job.
‐ Thank you.

41:52.885 --> 41:54.220
<i>To, like, my wife and my kids,</i>

41:54.220 --> 41:56.347
this just proves
that you can do anything.

41:56.347 --> 41:57.515
<i>It's just a matter of</i>
<i>putting your mind to it</i>

41:57.515 --> 41:58.683
and putting your heart in it.

41:58.683 --> 42:03.521
<i>♪ ♪</i>

42:03.521 --> 42:04.522
[hammer clanks]
